te><note type="comment" xml:lang="en"> (from *menta)</note></mentioned>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>III 14</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>10</biblScope></bibl>.— <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>519 сл.</biblScope></bibl></etym><etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>pʼitʼna</w> <gloss><q>mint</q></gloss></mentioned>, with the dissimilative voicing of the initial consonant, like in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ǵītrī"/> ‘cucumeber’ etc. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Ахвледиани"/><biblScope>41 сл.</biblScope></bibl>). <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/> <w>pʼitʼna</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="ru"> (из *pinta)</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en"> (from *pinta)</note></mentioned> is close to Mediterranean and European names for mint: <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/> <w>μινϑη</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/> <w>mentha</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/> <w>myata</w><note type="comment" xml:lang="ru"> (из *menta)</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="en"> (from *menta)</note></mentioned>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>III 14</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>10</biblScope></bibl>.— <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>519 сл.</biblScope></bibl></etym></entry></body></text></TEI>